<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Plutarch</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Sep 7, 2010; substantive revision Thu Dec 5, 2024</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Plutarch of Chaeronea in Boeotia (<em>ca</em>. 45&ndash;120 CE) was a
Platonist philosopher, best known to the general public as author of
his &ldquo;Parallel Lives&rdquo; of paired Greek and Roman statesmen
and military leaders. He was a voluminous writer, author also of a
collection of &ldquo;Moralia&rdquo; or &ldquo;Ethical Essays,&rdquo;
mostly in dialogue format, many of them devoted to philosophical
topics, but not at all limited to ethics.</p>

<p>
Plutarch&rsquo;s significance as a philosopher, on which this article
concentrates, lies in his attempt to do justice to Plato&rsquo;s work
as a whole, and to reconstruct a coherent and credible philosophical
system out of it, as Antiochus (1st c. BCE) tried to do and as
Plotinus will also do later (204&ndash;270 CE). Two moves are crucial
in this regard. First, Plutarch, unlike Antiochus, respects both the
skeptical/aporetic element in Plato (as marked by the tentativeness
with which Socrates and the other main speakers in his dialogues
regularly advance their views) but also the views apparently endorsed
by the main speakers of the dialogues, which were widely regarded as
Plato&rsquo;s own doctrines (e.g. Diogenes Laertius 3.51&ndash;2).
Second, Plutarch, again unlike Antiochus but like Pythagorean
Platonists, focuses primarily and quite strongly on the
<em>Timaeus</em> for his understanding of Plato&rsquo;s
&ldquo;doctrines,&rdquo; and his interpretation of this dialogue
shapes his understanding of the entirety of Plato&rsquo;s thought.
Plutarch maintains what one may call literal interpretation of the
<em>Timaeus</em>, according to which the world has come about in time
from two principles, the divine craftsman and the &ldquo;Indefinite
Dyad&rdquo;, a Pythagorean pair of principles espoused already by
Speusippus. While the divine craftsman accounts for the coming into
being of order, of <em>kosmos</em>, and for the identity of all
objects in the world, the Dyad accounts for disorder, which allegedly
prevailed before the world-creation.</p>

<p>
This metaphysical or principle dualism is further strengthened by the
assumption of two mediating entities through which the two principles,
God and the Dyad, operate; the Indefinite Dyad operates through a
non-rational cosmic soul, while God through a rational one. This is
the same soul, which becomes rational when God imparts reason from
himself to it. As a result of God&rsquo;s imparting reason to the
world soul, matter ceases to move in a disorderly manner, being
brought into order through the imposition of Forms on it. The
postulation of a non-rational pre-cosmic world soul, inspired mainly
by <em>Laws</em> X (but absent from the <em>Timaeus</em>), allows
Plutarch to dissolve an apparent contradiction in Plato&rsquo;s works
that the soul is both uncreated (<em>Phaedrus</em> 245c&ndash;246a)
and created (<em>Timaeus</em> 34b&ndash;36d). For in his view the soul
of the sensible world, the world soul, is created only in the sense
that God, the demiurge of the <em>Timaeus</em>, makes it rational. The
postulation of a non-rational pre-cosmic soul also allows Plutarch to
account for the existence of badness in the world, because in his view
residual irrationality abides in the world soul even when it becomes
rational, which is accounted for by the fact that the world soul is
originally and essentially non-rational, in the sense that its
movement is such, i.e. disorderly, and reason is an element external
to it, coming from the divine craftsman.</p>

<p>
This dualism (non-rational-disorderly-bad vs. rational-orderly-good)
pervades also the sensible or physical world, since the human soul,
being derivative from the world soul, exhibits a similar structure
with it and has a rational and a non-rational aspect too, as the
<em>Republic</em> and the <em>Timaeus</em> suggest. In this spirit,
Plutarch distinguishes both in the world and in human beings three
aspects, body, soul, and intellect. The soul&rsquo;s concern with the
body gives rise to the non-rational aspect, which amounts to disorder,
vice, or even badness, while the co-operation between soul and
intellect promotes rationality, that is, order, virtue, benevolence.
In an attempt to accommodate the diverse strands of ethical thought in
Plato (e.g. in the <em>Gorgias</em>, <em>Protagoras</em>,
<em>Republic</em>, <em>Phaedo</em>, <em>Theaetetus</em>,
<em>Timaeus</em>), Plutarch comes close to distinguish different
levels of ethical life, which we could term political or civic and
theoretical respectively, depending on whether virtue pertains to the
soul as an organizing principle for one&rsquo;s daily life within a
society, or to the human intellect as one&rsquo;s guide to knowledge,
especially knowledge of the Forms and of the intelligible realm, more
generally.</p>
</div> 

